            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": " `vim.cmd()` executes Vimscript. `\"\\<cr>\"` is [valid Vimscript](https://neovim.io/doc/user/usr_41.html#41.1:~:text=The%20%20%22%5C%3Cname%3E%22%20form%20can%20be%20used%20to%20include%0Athe%20special%20key%20%22name%22.) but it's not valid lua.\r\n\r\nFor example, if you run `:lua print(\"\\<cr>\")` you'll see an error:\r\n```\r\nE5107: Error loading lua [string \":lua\"]:1: invalid escape sequence near '\"'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThat's because lua is interpreting `\\<` as a C-like escape sequence, but `\\<` is not a valid escape sequence.\r\n\r\nWhat you want to do can be accomplished by using the lua `\" \"` (space) and `\"\\r\"` (carriage return) strings:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.g.mapleader = \"\\r\"\r\nvim.g.maplocalleader = \" \"\r\n```\r\n",
